"# Chapter 7 — String Ports

A PORT is Scheme's abstraction for something you can read from or
write to. R7RS gives you file ports and string ports. Motoi is
hermetic — no file I/O — but string ports work perfectly. They let
you 'write' to a string and 'read' from a string as if they were
files.

## Why string ports exist

Two big use cases:

- **Capture output.** You want to build a big string by writing
  many small pieces without calling `string-append` a hundred times.
  Open an output-string port, write to it, then call `get-output-string`
  to pull the whole thing out.
- **Replay input.** You have a string that you want to parse
  line-by-line or character-by-character. Open an input-string port
  and use `read-line`, `read-char`, or `peek-char`.

## Problem 1 — Capture output into a string

Build a formatted report without concatenating strings by hand.

```
(define port (open-output-string))

(write-string \"REPORT\\n\" port)
(write-string \"------\\n\" port)
(write-string \"Score: \" port)
(write 42 port)
(write-string \"\\n\" port)

(define report (get-output-string port))
(display report)
;; => REPORT
;;    ------
;;    Score: 42
```

Read the shape. `open-output-string` returns a port. `write-string`
appends to it. `write` writes any value in its machine-readable form
(strings get quotes, symbols don't). When you're done,
`get-output-string` returns the accumulated string.

## Problem 2 — Parse a string line by line

`open-input-string` gives you an input port; `read-line` pulls one
line at a time, stripping the newline.

```
(define input \"alice,30\\nbob,25\\ncarol,35\")
(define port (open-input-string input))

(display (read-line port))
;; => \"alice,30\"
(display (read-line port))
;; => \"bob,25\"
(display (read-line port))
;; => \"carol,35\"
(display (eof-object? (read-line port)))
;; => #t
```

At end-of-input, `read-line` returns the EOF object — the sentinel
that says 'nothing more'. `eof-object?` tests for it.

## Problem 3 — Look at the next character without consuming it

`peek-char` returns the next character but leaves it in the port.
Useful when the decision of what to do depends on what's next.

```
(define port (open-input-string \"123abc\"))

(display (peek-char port))
;; => \"1\"
(display (read-char port))
;; => \"1\"
(display (peek-char port))
;; => \"2\"
```

Notice: peek then read returns the same character. `read-char`
consumes, `peek-char` doesn't.

## Problem 4 (expert) — Read integers off the front of a string

Combine `peek-char`, `read-char`, and the character predicates from
Chapter 5 to parse.

```
(define (read-number port)
  (let loop ((acc \"\"))
    (let ((c (peek-char port)))
      (cond ((eof-object? c) (string->number acc))
            ((char-numeric? c)
             (read-char port)
             (loop (string-append acc c)))
            (else (string->number acc))))))

(define port (open-input-string \"42 apples\"))
(display (read-number port))
;; => 42
```

Read the shape. We `peek-char` to see what's next. If it's a digit,
consume it and add to the accumulator. If it's anything else (or
EOF), stop and return the number so far. This is the shape of a
recursive descent parser — one character of lookahead.

## Problem 5 — with-output-to-string convenience

Motoi provides `with-output-to-string` and `with-input-from-string`
as convenience wrappers. They take a thunk (a zero-argument function)
and run it with the current output redirected to a string port (or
input redirected from one).

```
(define captured
  (with-output-to-string
    (lambda ()
      (display \"hello, \")
      (display \"world\"))))

(display captured)
;; => \"hello, world\"
```

The thunk ran normally, but its output was captured into `captured`
instead of being printed to the terminal. That is the shape of a
mini-shell — run something and inspect what it said.

## Capstone — A simple line-oriented interpreter

Read a string of commands, one per line, dispatch each, capture the
output.

```
(define (run-command cmd)
  (cond ((equal? cmd \"hello\") \"hi there!\")
        ((equal? cmd \"time\") \"the current time is now.\")
        ((equal? cmd \"quit\") \"goodbye.\")
        (else (string-append \"unknown: \" cmd))))

(define (run-script script)
  (let ((in (open-input-string script))
        (out (open-output-string)))
    (let loop ()
      (let ((line (read-line in)))
        (cond ((eof-object? line) (get-output-string out))
              (else
                (write-string (run-command line) out)
                (write-string \"\\n\" out)
                (loop)))))))

(display (run-script \"hello\\ntime\\nquit\"))
;; => hi there!
;;    the current time is now.
;;    goodbye.
```

The shape composes everything: input port to read lines, output port
to accumulate responses, `run-command` as the dispatch, and a
tail-recursive `loop` that stops at EOF.

## Alphabet of string ports

- **Open:** `open-input-string`, `open-output-string`
- **Read:** `read-char`, `read-line`, `peek-char`
- **Write:** `write`, `write-char`, `write-string`
- **End:** `eof-object`, `eof-object?`
- **Finish:** `get-output-string`
- **Close:** `close-port`, `close-input-port`, `close-output-port`
- **Test:** `port?`, `input-port?`, `output-port?`
- **Convenience:** `with-output-to-string`, `with-input-from-string`

Nineteen verbs. Enough to build a mini-shell, a mini-parser, or a
report generator. Motoi never gives you real file I/O — but between
string ports and the rest of the library, you rarely notice.

## What's next

In Chapter 8 we turn to the numeric tower. R7RS distinguishes
integer / rational / real / complex; Motoi provides most of the
predicates and converters. That is how a Scheme handles
'what kind of number is this?' cleanly.
")
